  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why am I getting Likes from people in India when my ad campaign is targeted only to people in SF?",
  "response": "Receiving Likes from unexpected locations, such as India, despite targeting your ad campaign specifically to San Francisco (SF), can be puzzling. Here are several possible reasons for this occurrence and steps you can take to address it:\n\n1. **Ad Platform\u2019s Targeting Parameters:**\n   - **Geographical Overlays:** Some ad platforms allow for overlapping targeting parameters. Ensure that your campaign is not part of a broader campaign targeting multiple regions, including India.\n   - **Radius Targeting Errors:** If you\u2019re using radius-based targeting around SF, double-check that the radius isn\u2019t inadvertently large enough to include parts of neighboring regions that might extend internationally, though this is less likely.\n\n2. **VPNs and Proxy Usage:**\n   - **Misattributed Locations:** Users in India (or elsewhere) might be using Virtual Private Networks (VPNs) or proxies that mask their actual location, making the ad platform believe they are accessing from SF. This can lead to them seeing and interacting with ads meant for SF.\n\n3. **Ad Sharing and Virality:**\n   - **Content Sharing:** If your ad content is engaging or shareable, individuals in India might be sharing it with their networks, leading to Likes from outside your targeted area.\n   - **Global Reach Features:** Some platforms optimize for engagement and might extend your ad\u2019s reach beyond the specified location to maximize interactions.\n\n4. **Technical Glitches or Errors:**\n   - **Platform Bugs:** Occasionally, ad platforms may have glitches that misreport the locations of interactions. Check if there are any reported issues with the platform you\u2019re using.\n   - **Incorrect Campaign Settings:** Review your campaign settings thoroughly to ensure that all targeting parameters are correctly set to SF without any unintended inclusions.\n\n5. **Cross-Device and Account Linking:**\n   - **Shared Devices:** If someone in SF shares their device with someone in India, interactions might be mistakenly attributed to the SF campaign.\n   - **Multiple Accounts Usage:** Users with multiple accounts or those who have recently relocated might inadvertently like your page from different locations.\n\n6. **Third-Party Integrations:**\n   - **External Websites and Apps:** If your ad is being displayed through third-party websites or apps that have a global audience, this might result in broader geographical interactions.\n   - **Retargeting Campaigns:** Ensure that any retargeting or lookalike audience campaigns are also correctly scoped to your desired geography.\n\n**Steps to Mitigate and Investigate Further:**\n\n1. **Review Campaign Settings:**\n   - Double-check the geographical targeting settings in your ad campaign to ensure it\u2019s strictly limited to SF.\n   - Verify that there are no additional targeting layers (like language or interest-based targeting) that might inadvertently include a broader audience.\n\n2. **Analyze Ad Placement:**\n   - Look into where your ads are being displayed. Some placements might have a more global audience, which can lead to unintended interactions.\n\n3. **Monitor Engagement Metrics:**\n   - Use analytics tools provided by the ad platform to monitor where your engagements (Likes) are coming from.\n   - Track any patterns or spikes that correlate with the unexpected Likes.\n\n4. **Contact Platform Support:**\n   - Reach out to the support team of the ad platform you\u2019re using. Provide them with details of the issue\u2014they might offer insights or identify if it\u2019s a known issue.\n\n5. **Implement Location Restrictions:**\n   - Some platforms allow you to exclude certain regions or countries explicitly. Consider adding India to your exclusion list to prevent further Likes from that region.\n\n6. **Enhance Ad Verification:**\n   - Use third-party tools or services that offer more robust ad verification to ensure your ads are reaching the intended audience.\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nWhile precise geographical targeting is a powerful feature, it\u2019s not always foolproof due to factors like VPN usage, sharing behaviors, and platform-specific nuances. By systematically reviewing your campaign settings, monitoring engagement data, and leveraging platform support, you can better understand and mitigate the occurrence of Likes from unintended locations like India.\n\nIf the issue persists despite these measures, it might be worthwhile to explore alternative ad strategies or platforms that offer more granular control over audience targeting.",
